00:12:02,683 --> 00:12:04,783
to Pam.

312
00:12:04,785 --> 00:12:06,151
Let's see.

313
00:12:06,153 --> 00:12:07,819
I had an aunt

314
00:12:07,821 --> 00:12:09,321
that I was really close to.

315
00:12:09,323 --> 00:12:12,391
She was this amazing
female boxer.

316
00:12:12,393 --> 00:12:15,594
Um, anyway,
she was injured in a fight,

317
00:12:15,596 --> 00:12:17,496
and she was paralyzed.

318
00:12:17,498 --> 00:12:21,800
So you can imagine
how upset I was...

319
00:12:21,802 --> 00:12:23,068
when I found out

320
00:12:23,070 --> 00:12:24,970
that she asked her manager

321
00:12:24,972 --> 00:12:27,005
to remove her breathing tube

322
00:12:27,007 --> 00:12:30,175
so she could die.

323
00:12:30,177 --> 00:12:32,744
Wow.

324
00:12:32,746 --> 00:12:35,180
If you want to cry, that's okay.

325
00:12:39,886 --> 00:12:41,353
Thanks.
Um...

326
00:12:41,355 --> 00:12:42,921
A few years ago,

327
00:12:42,923 --> 00:12:45,490
my family was
on a safari in Africa.

328
00:12:45,492 --> 00:12:49,294
And, um, my cousin...
Mufasa...

329
00:12:49,296 --> 00:12:53,098
was, um, he was
trampled to death

330
00:12:53,100 --> 00:12:54,966
by a pack of wildebeests.

331
00:12:54,968 --> 00:13:00,172
And, um, we all...
took it really hard.

332
00:13:00,174 --> 00:13:03,341
All of us kind
of in the audience...

333
00:13:03,343 --> 00:13:04,709
of what happened.

334
00:13:04,711 --> 00:13:06,878
Do you wanna
talk about it anymore?

335
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:09,114
Oh, it would probably
take me, like,

336
00:13:09,116 --> 00:13:11,349
an hour and a half
to tell that whole story.

337
00:13:11,351 --> 00:13:12,417
Me me, me me me.

338
00:13:12,419 --> 00:13:14,386
Yes. Okay.

339
00:13:14,388 --> 00:13:18,390
Um... I was trying
to throw this party once.

340
00:13:18,392 --> 00:13:22,060
And everyone was over
for the weekend.

341
00:13:22,062 --> 00:13:25,864
And then my Uncle Bernie died.

342
00:13:25,866 --> 00:13:28,733
And so me and

343
00:13:28,735 --> 00:13:29,968
my best friend,

344
00:13:29,970 --> 00:13:32,838
we had to pretend
like he was alive.

345
00:13:32,840 --> 00:13:34,506
So...

346
00:13:34,508 --> 00:13:36,274
Wait a second.

347
00:13:37,477 --> 00:13:39,010
That's Weekend at Bernie's.

348
00:13:40,380 --> 00:13:42,380
Do you think that this
is a game?

349
00:13:42,382 --> 00:13:43,748
Well, there is a ball.

350
00:13:43,750 --> 00:13:44,783
All right, we're starting over.

351
00:13:44,785 --> 00:13:46,084
No, I'm done.

352
00:13:46,086 --> 00:13:48,019
You are not leaving!
No, we are not done.

353
00:13:48,021 --> 00:13:49,588
We really have
a lot of work to do.

354
00:13:49,590 --> 00:13:50,655
Yeah, well, you know what?

355
00:13:50,657 --> 00:13:53,925
The guy who had my job has died.

356
00:13:53,927 --> 00:13:56,094
And nobody cares.

357
00:13:56,096 --> 00:13:58,230
And he sat at my desk.

358
00:13:58,232 --> 00:13:59,831
Michael...

359
00:13:59,833 --> 00:14:02,601
Look, I know
this is hard for you.

360
00:14:02,603 --> 00:14:04,503
But death's just a part of life.

361
00:14:04,505 --> 00:14:06,204
I mean, just this morning,
I saw a little bird

362
00:14:06,206 --> 00:14:09,341
fly into the glass doors
downstairs and die.

363
00:14:09,343 --> 00:14:11,243
And I had to keep going.

364
00:14:11,245 --> 00:14:12,711
How do you know?
What?

365
00:14:12,713 --> 00:14:14,546
That that bird was dead?

366
00:14:14,548 --> 00:14:16,548
Did you check...
its breathing?

367
00:14:16,550 --> 00:14:17,616
It was obvious.

368
00:14:17,618 --> 00:14:19,351
Was its heart beating, Toby?

369
00:14:19,353 --> 00:14:21,586
Did you check it?
No, of course you didn't.

370
00:14:21,588 --> 00:14:22,921
You're not a veterinarian.

371
00:14:22,923 --> 00:14:24,823
You don't know anything!

372
00:14:24,825 --> 00:14:26,224
Michael!

373
00:14:26,226 --> 00:14:30,095
Michael!

374
00:14:30,097 --> 00:14:32,597
Michael!

375
00:14:32,599 --> 00:14:33,698
Michael...

376
00:14:33,700 --> 00:14:34,766
Oh, God.

377
00:14:34,768 --> 00:14:36,301
Ohh!
Oh, my God!

378
00:14:36,303 --> 00:14:38,436
Oh, my God!
Come on.

379
00:14:38,438 --> 00:14:39,471
Poor little fella.

380
00:14:39,473 --> 00:14:40,839
- Oh, shoot.
- He's a goner.

381
00:14:40,841 --> 00:14:42,474
- No, he's not.
- Yeah.

382
00:14:42,476 --> 00:14:43,542
No, he's not.

383
00:14:43,544 --> 00:14:44,943
Michael, get him
away from your head!

384
00:14:44,945 --> 00:14:46,211
He is covered
in germs and bacteria!

385
00:14:46,213 --> 00:14:48,780
You can't get
diseases from a bird!

386
00:14:49,482 --> 00:14:51,383
A dead bird should not
be in the kitchen.

387
00:14:51,385 --> 00:14:52,417
We don't know if it's dead.

388
00:14:52,419 --> 00:14:55,186
Uh, no, that thing is dead.

389
00:14:55,188 --> 00:14:56,488
You want me to flush him?

390
00:14:58,357 --> 00:15:00,358
Attention, everybody.

391
00:15:00,360 --> 00:15:02,227
This will only take a second...

392
00:15:02,229 --> 00:15:04,729
of your time.

393
00:15:04,731 --> 00:15:06,331
Today at 4:00 p.m.,

394
00:15:06,333 --> 00:15:08,867
we will be meeting
in the parking lot

395
00:15:08,869 --> 00:15:13,271
to have a funeral service
for this bird.

396
00:15:13,273 --> 00:15:14,439
I have a lot of work to do.

397
00:15:14,441 --> 00:15:17,242
Well... I'm sorry
to inconvenience you,

398
00:15:17,244 --> 00:15:18,543
Meredith.

399
00:15:18,545 --> 00:15:21,279
But that is what you do
when things die.

400
00:15:21,281 --> 00:15:22,614
You honor them.

401
00:15:22,616 --> 00:15:24,349
Toby killed this bird.

402
00:15:24,351 --> 00:15:25,951
And now we are going
to honor it.

403
00:15:25,953 --> 00:15:27,419
- But...
- No! No! No!

404
00:15:27,421 --> 00:15:28,553
That's enough.
You know what?

405
00:15:28,555 --> 00:15:30,989
This bird is dead.

406
00:15:30,991 --> 00:15:32,057
It died alone.

407
00:15:32,059 --> 00:15:33,558
The least you can do

408
00:15:33,560 --> 00:15:36,861
is be there for him now.

409
00:15:38,898 --> 00:15:40,699
Find a box for him.

410
00:15:40,701 --> 00:15:43,268
I'm calling a supermarket
in Montreal.

411
00:15:43,270 --> 00:15:44,502
Nice.

412
00:15:44,504 --> 00:15:46,538
Bonjour, je cherche

413
00:15:46,540 --> 00:15:48,740
de chips de la marque Herr's.

414
00:15:48,742 --> 00:15:50,342
Non?

415
00:15:50,344 --> 00:15:53,244
Oh, merci comme mÃªme.

416
00:15:53,246 --> 00:15:54,613
Au revoir.

417
00:15:54,615 --> 00:15:55,680
Nope.

418
00:15:55,682 --> 00:15:57,616
- Sounded good.
- Thanks.

419
00:16:06,359 --> 00:16:08,093
It's okay.

420
00:16:08,095 --> 00:16:09,494
It's okay.

421
00:16:09,496 --> 00:16:11,396
Shh.
Yes, I know.

422
00:16:11,398 --> 00:16:13,231
I know it's been a tough day.

423
00:16:13,233 --> 00:16:15,166
But it's good to let it show.

424
00:16:15,168 --> 00:16:18,470
I mean, how many times
do I have to confirm plans

425
00:16:18,472 --> 00:16:21,373
with Ryan for him to know
that we have a date tonight?

426
00:16:25,277 --> 00:16:27,746
God.

427
00:16:27,748 --> 00:16:29,247
What are...

428
00:16:29,249 --> 00:16:30,548
What are you doing?

429
00:16:30,550 --> 00:16:31,883
What?

430
00:16:31,885 --> 00:16:33,184
No, this is
about the right size.

431
00:16:33,186 --> 00:16:35,553
No, God, no!
It's not!

432
00:16:35,555 --> 00:16:37,122
What is the matter with you?

433
00:16:37,124 --> 00:16:38,623
Is that the beak?

434
00:16:40,026 --> 00:16:42,627
I'm sorry, I grew up on a farm.

435
00:16:42,629 --> 00:16:45,463
We slaughtered a pig
whenever we wanted bacon.

436
00:16:45,465 --> 00:16:48,600
My grandfather was re-buried
in an old oil drum.

437
00:16:50,136 --> 00:16:53,605
It would've fit if he had
given me another minute.

438
00:16:53,607 --> 00:16:55,473
I need a box.

439
00:16:55,475 --> 00:16:57,876
I need a box, a small box.

440
00:16:57,878 --> 00:17:00,178
Not too confining.

441
00:17:00,180 --> 00:17:01,513
- Is it for the bird?
- Yeah.

442
00:17:01,515 --> 00:17:02,647
I have it covered.

443
00:17:02,649 --> 00:17:04,849
Oh, thank you.

444
00:17:06,186 --> 00:17:07,986
If you want to do something
for the funeral...

445
00:17:07,988 --> 00:17:09,387
Yes, please.

446
00:17:09,389 --> 00:17:10,989
Maybe you could play a song
on your recorder. Excellent.

447
00:17:10,991 --> 00:17:12,891
Do you have it with you?
Always.

448
00:17:15,728 --> 00:17:17,662
Did I wake up this morning
thinking I'd be

449
00:17:17,664 --> 00:17:19,397
throwing together
a bird funeral?

450
00:17:20,533 --> 00:17:22,333
You never can tell
what your day here

451
00:17:22,335 --> 00:17:23,902
is gonna turn into.

452
00:17:27,740 --> 00:17:30,141
Where'd you find them?

453
00:17:30,143 --> 00:17:31,976
Where'd I find what?

454
00:17:40,152 --> 00:17:41,653
I called the manufacturer,

455
00:17:41,655 --> 00:17:43,688
who referred me
to the distributor,

456
00:17:43,690 --> 00:17:45,790
who referred me
to the vending machine company,

457
00:17:45,792 --> 00:17:48,259
who told me that
they sell them in the machines

458
00:17:48,261 --> 00:17:49,994
in the building next door.

459
00:17:49,996 --> 00:17:51,930
Glad you could all make it.

460
00:17:51,932 --> 00:17:53,431
You told us we had to.

461
00:17:53,433 --> 00:17:55,200
Dwight, do you have the box?

462
00:17:55,202 --> 00:17:56,935
Actually, I have it.

463
00:17:59,839 --> 00:18:01,873
You made this?

464
00:18:01,875 --> 00:18:03,541
Wow.

465
00:18:03,543 --> 00:18:06,878
That's...
that's very nice.

466
00:18:06,880 --> 00:18:08,880
When I was five, my mom told me

467
00:18:08,882 --> 00:18:10,815
that my fish
went to the hospital

468
00:18:10,817 --> 00:18:12,283
in the toilet.

469
00:18:12,285 --> 00:18:14,185
And it never came back.

470
00:18:14,187 --> 00:18:16,087
So we had a funeral for it.

471
00:18:16,089 --> 00:18:17,455
And I remember thinking,

472
00:18:17,457 --> 00:18:19,491
"I'm a little too old
for this."

473
00:18:19,493 --> 00:18:22,527
And I was five.

474
00:18:22,529 --> 00:18:23,862
I'd also like
to say a few words,

475
00:18:23,864 --> 00:18:25,130
if that's okay.

476
00:18:26,665 --> 00:18:28,032
Yes.

477
00:18:28,034 --> 00:18:31,069
What do we know about this bird?

478
00:18:31,071 --> 00:18:34,439
You might think,
"Not much, it's just a bird."

479
00:18:34,441 --> 00:18:36,541
But we do know some things.

480
00:18:36,543 --> 00:18:39,611
We know it was a local bird.

481
00:18:39,613 --> 00:18:43,181
Maybe it's that same bird
that surprised Oscar

482
00:18:43,183 --> 00:18:46,050
that one morning with
a special present from above.

483
00:18:46,052 --> 00:18:48,186
Oh, I remember that.
That was so funny.

484
00:18:48,188 --> 00:18:49,954
And we know how he died.

485
00:18:49,956 --> 00:18:52,891
Flying into the glass doors.

486
00:18:52,893 --> 00:18:54,125
But you know what,

487
00:18:54,127 --> 00:18:56,161
I don't think
he was being stupid.

488
00:18:56,163 --> 00:18:58,630
I think he just...

489
00:18:58,632 --> 00:19:01,499
really, really wanted
to come inside our building

490
00:19:01,501 --> 00:19:04,169
to spread his cheer

491
00:19:04,171 --> 00:19:06,504
and lift our spirits
with a song.

492
00:19:06,506 --> 00:19:08,239
- It's not a songbird.
- Shh.

493
00:19:08,241 --> 00:19:09,808
An impression, then.

494
00:19:09,810 --> 00:19:12,844
Lastly, we can't help but notice

495
00:19:12,846 --> 00:19:14,979
that he was by himself
when he died.

496
00:19:14,981 --> 00:19:16,848
But of course, we all know

497
00:19:16,850 --> 00:19:19,450
that doesn't mean he was alone.

498
00:19:19,452 --> 00:19:20,752
Because I'm sure

499
00:19:20,754 --> 00:19:22,453
that there were lots
of other birds

500
00:19:22,455 --> 00:19:23,855
out there who cared for him

501
00:19:23,857 --> 00:19:26,090
very much.

502
00:19:26,092 --> 00:19:28,526
He will not be forgotten.
Amen.

503
00:19:43,476 --> 00:19:45,510
Society teaches us

504
00:19:45,512 --> 00:19:49,781
that having feelings and crying

505
00:19:49,783 --> 00:19:52,417
is bad and wrong.

506
00:19:52,419 --> 00:19:55,053
Well, that's baloney,

507
00:19:55,055 --> 00:19:59,290
because grief isn't wrong.

508
00:19:59,292 --> 00:20:01,759
There is such a thing
as good grief.

509
00:20:01,761 --> 00:20:04,195
Just ask Charlie Brown.

510
00:20:10,904 --> 00:20:13,037
Let's get back to work.

511
00:20:27,353 --> 00:20:28,620
Guys, get a broom.

512
00:20:28,622 --> 00:20:30,154
Let's clean this up.

513
00:20:30,156 --> 00:20:31,756
Grab a broom.

514
00:20:31,758 --> 00:20:33,825
You heard me.
Mush.

